Introduction to data

Some define statistics as the field that focuses on turning information into knowledge. The first step in that process is to summarize and describe the raw information the data. In this lab we explore flights, specifically a random sample of domestic flights that departed from the three major New York City airports in 2013. We will generate simple graphical and numerical summaries of data on these flights and explore delay times. Since this is a large data set, along the way youll also learn the indispensable skills of data processing and subsetting.

Getting started

Load packages

In this lab, we will explore and visualize the data using the tidyverse suite of packages. The data can be found in the companion package for OpenIntro labs, openintro.

Lets load the packages.

library(tidyverse)
library(openintro)

The data

The Bureau of Transportation Statistics (BTS) is a statistical agency that is a part of the Research and Innovative Technology Administration (RITA). As its name implies, BTS collects and makes transportation data available, such as the flights data we will be working with in this lab.

First, well view the nycflights data frame. Type the following in your console to load the data:

data(nycflights)

The data set nycflights that shows up in your workspace is a data matrix, with each row representing an observation and each column representing a variable. R calls this data format a data frame, which is a term that will be used throughout the labs. For this data set, each observation is a single flight.

To view the names of the variables, type the command

names(nycflights)

Analysis

Departure delays

Lets start by examing the distribution of departure delays of all flights with a histogram.

ggplot(data = nycflights, aes(x = dep_delay)) +
  geom_histogram()

This function says to plot the dep_delay variable from the nycflights data frame on the x-axis. It also defines a geom (short for geometric object), which describes the type of plot you will produce.

Histograms are generally a very good way to see the shape of a single distribution of numerical data, but that shape can change depending on how the data is split between the different bins. You can easily define the binwidth you want to use:

ggplot(data = nycflights, aes(x = dep_delay)) +
  geom_histogram(binwidth = 15)

ggplot(data = nycflights, aes(x = dep_delay)) +
  geom_histogram(binwidth = 150)

  1. Look carefully at these three histograms. How do they compare? Are features revealed in one that are obscured in another?

When we look at histograms with different bin widths, we see how the level of detail changes. The second histogram has the smallest bin width, so it shows the data with the most detail. The third histogram has the largest bin width, which groups much of the data together and hides some details. The first histogram has a bin width thats in between the other two, showing a good amount of detail thats easier to understand and visually appealing. Even though the second histogram shows the most detail, the first one provides a nice balance and is easier on the eyes.

If you want to visualize only on delays of flights headed to Los Angeles, you need to first filter the data for flights with that destination (dest == "LAX") and then make a histogram of the departure delays of only those flights.

lax_flights <- nycflights %>%
  filter(dest == "LAX")
ggplot(data = lax_flights, aes(x = dep_delay)) +
  geom_histogram()

Lets decipher these two commands (OK, so it might look like four lines, but the first two physical lines of code are actually part of the same command. Its common to add a break to a new line after %>% to help readability).

  • Command 1: Take the nycflights data frame, filter for flights headed to LAX, and save the result as a new data frame called lax_flights.
    • == means if its equal to.
    • LAX is in quotation marks since it is a character string.
  • Command 2: Basically the same ggplot call from earlier for making a histogram, except that it uses the smaller data frame for flights headed to LAX instead of all flights.

Logical operators: Filtering for certain observations (e.g.flights from a particular airport) is often of interest in data frames where we might want to examine observations with certain characteristics separately from the rest of the data. To do so, you can use the filter function and a series of logical operators. The most commonly used logical operators for data analysis are as follows:

  • == means equal to
  • != means not equal to
  • > or < means greater than or less than
  • >= or <= means greater than or equal to or less than or equal to

You can also obtain numerical summaries for these flights:

lax_flights %>%
  summarise(mean_dd   = mean(dep_delay), 
            median_dd = median(dep_delay), 
            n         = n())
## # A tibble: 1  3
##   mean_dd median_dd     n
##     <dbl>     <dbl> <int>
## 1    9.78        -1  1583

Note that in the summarise function you created a list of three different numerical summaries that you were interested in. The names of these elements are user defined, like mean_dd, median_dd, n, and you can customize these names as you like (just dont use spaces in your names). Calculating these summary statistics also requires that you know the function calls. Note that n() reports the sample size.

Summary statistics: Some useful function calls for summary statistics for a single numerical variable are as follows:

  • mean
  • median
  • sd
  • var
  • IQR
  • min
  • max

Note that each of these functions takes a single vector as an argument and returns a single value.

You can also filter based on multiple criteria. Suppose you are interested in flights headed to San Francisco (SFO) in February:

sfo_feb_flights <- nycflights %>%
  filter(dest == "SFO", month == 2)

Note that you can separate the conditions using commas if you want flights that are both headed to SFO and in February. If you are interested in either flights headed to SFO or in February, you can use the | instead of the comma.

  1. Create a new data frame that includes flights headed to SFO in February, and save this data frame as sfo_feb_flights. How many flights meet these criteria?

To create a new data frame that includes flights headed to San Francisco (SFO) in February, we can use the following code (Part of lab example only above):

sfo_feb_flights <- nycflights %>%
  filter(dest == "SFO", month == 2)

To determine the number of flights that meet these criteria, we can use the n() function inside summarise:

sfo_feb_flights %>%
  summarise(num_flights = n())
## # A tibble: 1  1
##   num_flights
##         <int>
## 1          68

Breakdown of code:

Filter Data: The filter function subsets the data to include only flights headed to SFO in February. Count Flights: The summarise function calculates the number of flights in the filtered data frame.

There are 68 flights from the dataset that are headed to San Francisco (SFO) in February.

  1. Describe the distribution of the arrival delays of these flights using a histogram and appropriate summary statistics. Hint: The summary statistics you use should depend on the shape of the distribution.

To describe the distribution of arrival delays for flights headed to San Francisco (SFO) in February, I followed below steps:

ggplot(data = sfo_feb_flights, aes(x = arr_delay)) +
  geom_histogram(binwidth = 10) +  # We can adjust binwidth as required
  labs(title = "Histogram of Arrival Delays for SFO Flights in second month - February",
       x = "Arrival Delay (minutes)", y = "Frequency")

Calculating Summary Statistics:

sfo_feb_flights %>%
  summarise(
    mean_ad     = mean(arr_delay, na.rm = TRUE),  # Mean arrival delay
    median_ad   = median(arr_delay, na.rm = TRUE),  # Median arrival delay
    iqr_ad      = IQR(arr_delay, na.rm = TRUE),  # Interquartile range
    n_flights   = n()  # Number of flights
  )
## # A tibble: 1  4
##   mean_ad median_ad iqr_ad n_flights
##     <dbl>     <dbl>  <dbl>     <int>
## 1    -4.5       -11   23.2        68

Note:- The na.rm = TRUE argument is added to handle any missing values in the arr_delay column.

Explanation

1. Mean: Average arrival delay. 2. Median: The middle value of the arrival delays, which is robust to outliers. 3. Interquartile Range (IQR): Measures the spread of the middle 50% of arrival delays.

The histogram shows a right-skewed distribution, which means the standard deviation may not effectively capture the spread of the data. In contrast, the interquartile range (IQR) provides a better description of how the central 50% of the data is distributed around the median.

Another useful technique is quickly calculating summary statistics for various groups in your data frame. For example, we can modify the above command using the group_by function to get the same summary stats for each origin airport:

sfo_feb_flights %>%
  group_by(origin) %>%
  summarise(median_dd = median(dep_delay), iqr_dd = IQR(dep_delay), n_flights = n())
## # A tibble: 2  4
##   origin median_dd iqr_dd n_flights
##   <chr>      <dbl>  <dbl>     <int>
## 1 EWR          0.5   5.75         8
## 2 JFK         -2.5  15.2         60

Here, we first grouped the data by origin and then calculated the summary statistics.

  1. Calculate the median and interquartile range for arr_delays of flights in in the sfo_feb_flights data frame, grouped by carrier. Which carrier has the most variable arrival delays?
sfo_feb_flights %>%
  group_by(carrier) %>%
  summarise(median_ad = median(arr_delay, na.rm = TRUE),  # Median arrival delay
    iqr_ad = IQR(arr_delay, na.rm = TRUE)  # Interquartile range of arrival delay
  ) %>%
  
  arrange(desc(iqr_ad))  # Sorting by IQR to see the most variable carrier we have
## # A tibble: 5  3

##   <chr>       <dbl>  <dbl>
## 1 DL          -15     22  
## 2 UA          -10     22  
## 3 VX          -22.5   21.2
## 4 AA            5     17.5
## 5 B6          -10.5   12.2

The carriers DL and UA have the highest variability in arrival delays, as both have the largest interquartile range of 22.00. This indicates that the arrival delays for the middle 50% of their flights show the greatest variation.

Departure delays by month

Which month would you expect to have the highest average delay departing from an NYC airport?

Lets think about how you could answer this question:

  • First, calculate monthly averages for departure delays. With the new language you are learning, you could
    • group_by months, then
    • summarise mean departure delays.
  • Then, you could to arrange these average delays in descending order
nycflights %>%
  group_by(month) %>%
  summarise(mean_dd = mean(dep_delay)) %>%
  arrange(desc(mean_dd))

I would anticipate that the holiday season (December) or the summer vacation months (June and July) would experience the longest average departure delays from NYC airports due to increased traffic. It turns out that July has the highest average departure delay from an NYC airport.

  1. Suppose you really dislike departure delays and you want to schedule your travel in a month that minimizes your potential departure delay leaving NYC. One option is to choose the month with the lowest mean departure delay. Another option is to choose the month with the lowest median departure delay. What are the pros and cons of these two choices?
# Calculate mean and median departure delays by month
monthly_delays <- nycflights %>%
  group_by(month) %>%
  summarise(
    mean_dep_delay = mean(dep_delay, na.rm = TRUE),
    median_dep_delay = median(dep_delay, na.rm = TRUE)
  ) %>%
  
  arrange(mean_dep_delay, median_dep_delay)

# Print the results
print(monthly_delays)
## # A tibble: 12  3
##    month mean_dep_delay median_dep_delay
##    <int>          <dbl>            <dbl>
##  1    10           5.88               -3
##  2    11           6.10               -2
##  3     9           6.87               -3
##  4     1          10.2                -2
##  5     2          10.7                -2
##  6     8          12.6                -1
##  7     5          13.3                -1
##  8     3          13.5                -1
##  9     4          14.6                -2
## 10    12          17.4                 1
## 11     6          20.4                 0
## 12     7          20.8                 0
# Finding the month with the lowest mean departure delay
month_lowest_mean <- monthly_delays %>%
  filter(mean_dep_delay == min(mean_dep_delay))

# Finding the month with the lowest median departure delay
month_lowest_median <- monthly_delays %>%
  filter(median_dep_delay == min(median_dep_delay))

# Print the results
print(paste("Lowest mean departure delay month wise:", month_lowest_mean$month))
## [1] "Lowest mean departure delay month wise: 10"
print(paste("Lowest median departure delay month wise:", month_lowest_median$month))
## [1] "Lowest median departure delay month wise: 10"
## [2] "Lowest median departure delay month wise: 9"

Answer

Mean 1. Advantage: The mean provides the overall average departure delay, reflecting the impact of all delays and giving a sense of the general distribution of the data. 2. Disadvantage: It can be influenced by outliers, which might skew the average higher or lower than what most travelers experience.

Median 1. Advantage: The median represents the middle value of the data set, making it resistant to the effects of outliers and providing a clearer picture of the typical experience. 2. Disadvantage: It does not account for the distribution of delays and may not fully reflect variations in the data beyond the central value.**

On time departure rate for NYC airports

Suppose you will be flying out of NYC and want to know which of the three major NYC airports has the best on time departure rate of departing flights. Also supposed that for you, a flight that is delayed for less than 5 minutes is basically on time. You consider any flight delayed for 5 minutes of more to be delayed.

In order to determine which airport has the best on time departure rate, you can

  • first classify each flight as on time or delayed,
  • then group flights by origin airport,
  • then calculate on time departure rates for each origin airport,
  • and finally arrange the airports in descending order for on time departure percentage.

Lets start with classifying each flight as on time or delayed by creating a new variable with the mutate function.

nycflights <- nycflights %>%
  mutate(dep_type = ifelse(dep_delay < 5, "on time", "delayed"))

The first argument in the mutate function is the name of the new variable we want to create, in this case dep_type. Then if dep_delay < 5, we classify the flight as "on time" and "delayed" if not, i.e.if the flight is delayed for 5 or more minutes.

Note that we are also overwriting the nycflights data frame with the new version of this data frame that includes the new dep_type variable.

We can handle all of the remaining steps in one code chunk:

nycflights %>%
  group_by(origin) %>%
  summarise(ot_dep_rate = sum(dep_type == "on time") / n()) %>%
  arrange(desc(ot_dep_rate))
## # A tibble: 3  2
##   origin ot_dep_rate
##   <chr>        <dbl>
## 1 LGA          0.728
## 2 JFK          0.694
## 3 EWR          0.637
  1. If you were selecting an airport simply based on on time departure percentage, which NYC airport would you choose to fly out of?

You can also visualize the distribution of on on time departure rate across the three airports using a segmented bar plot.

ggplot(data = nycflights, aes(x = origin, fill = dep_type)) +
  geom_bar()

LGA boasts the highest on-time departure rate, with 72.8% of flights departing on time. The segmented bar plot also confirms that LGA has the greatest proportion of on-time departures. Consequently, I would opt to fly from LGA.

More Practice

  1. Mutate the data frame so that it includes a new variable that contains the average speed, avg_speed traveled by the plane for each flight (in mph). Hint: Average speed can be calculated as distance divided by number of hours of travel, and note that air_time is given in minutes.
nycflights <- nycflights %>%
  mutate(avg_speed = distance / (air_time / 60))  # Convert air_time from minutes to hours

Explanation:

mutate(avg_speed = distance / (air_time / 60)): distance is the distance traveled by the plane in miles. air_time is the travel time in minutes, so dividing it by 60 converts it to hours. distance / (air_time / 60) computes the average speed in miles per hour (mph).

By running above code, we can create a new variable avg_speed in the nycflights data frame that represents the average speed for each flight.

  1. Make a scatterplot of avg_speed vs.distance. Describe the relationship between average speed and distance. Hint: Use geom_point().
library(ggplot2)
ggplot(nycflights, aes(x = distance, y = avg_speed)) +

  1. Replicate the following plot. Hint: The data frame plotted only contains flights from American Airlines, Delta Airlines, and United Airlines, and the points are colored by carrier. Once you replicate the plot, determine (roughly) what the cutoff point is for departure delays where you can still expect to get to your destination on time.
# Filtering the data for American Airlines, Delta Airlines, and United Airlines with arrival delays less than 5 minutes

filtered_flights <- nycflights %>%
  filter(carrier %in% c("AA", "DL", "UA"), arr_delay < 5)

# Creating the scatterplot

plot <- ggplot(data = filtered_flights, aes(x = dep_delay, y = arr_delay, color = carrier)) +
  geom_point() +  # Add points for the scatterplot
  geom_line(aes(x = 45), color = "purple", linetype = "dotted") +  # Add a vertical line at x = 45
  geom_text(aes(x = 25, y = -30, label = "Cut-off for on-time arrival"), vjust = 0, hjust = 0) +
  labs(
    title = "Departure Delay vs. Arrival Delay for On-Time Arrivals", x = "Departure Delay (minutes)",
    y = "Arrival Delay (minutes)", color = "Carrier") 

# Printing the plot
print(plot)

The plot visualizes the relationship between departure and arrival delays for flights from American Airlines, Delta Airlines, and United Airlines, with a focus on flights arriving on time. A vertical dotted line at around 40-45 minutes illustrates the cutoff point where departing late can still result in on-time arrivals. The text label highlights this critical threshold, emphasizing that flights departing up to 40-45 minutes late may still reach their destination on time.

# Filter the data for American Airlines, Delta Airlines, and United Airlines
special_group <- nycflights %>%
  filter(carrier %in% c("AA", "DL", "UA"))

# Calculate the average departure delay for on-time or early arrivals, grouped by carrier
result <- special_group %>%
  filter(arr_delay <= 0) %>%
  group_by(carrier) %>%
  summarize(
    avg_departure_delay = mean(dep_delay, na.rm = TRUE)
  ) %>%
  arrange(desc(avg_departure_delay))

# Print the result
print(result)

Above code calculates and displays the average departure delay for flights arriving on time or early, grouped by carrier. It shows which carrier has the highest average departure delay for flights that still arrived on time.

The analysis suggests that if a flight departs approximately 40-45 minutes late, theres still a chance of arriving at the destination on time. To further explore this, we could segment the data by distance and examine how the allowable departure delay for on-time arrivals varies with distance.
